{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Lst7YVaqQnbZHy6H9sYzqg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting - only GC logs. The ES server logs in JSON format (like `es-cluster_server.json`) are not showing up. Let me check why. Maybe ES logs are going to stdout, not to files. In ES 8.x default docker setup, logs go to stdout/stderr instead of files.\n\nActually in ES Docker containers, by default logs go to stdout. The ES 8.x Docker image is configured to log to stdout only (not to files) by default. The only file-based logs are GC logs.\n\nSo for Filebeat to collect logs, I should either:\n1. Configure ES to log to files (by adding `path.logs` and appropriate log4j2 config)\n2. Use Filebeat's container log input to read from Docker/container logs (not applicable here since we're in Kubernetes)\n3. Use Filebeat's kubernetes log input to read from the pod's stdout logs (from the node's `/var/log/containers`)\n\nThe most practical approach for Filebeat to read ES logs in Kubernetes is to use Filebeat with access to the host's `/var/log/containers/` or `/var/log/pods/` directories, but that would require mounting the host path, which differs from a pure sidecar approach. Alternatively, I could use the `filestream` or `container` input type in Filebeat to read directly from the container's stderr/stdout.\n\nFor a sidecar setup, the cleaner option is to configure Elasticsearch to write logs to a shared emptyDir volume rather than relying on hostPath access, which avoids needing elevated privileges. Since Elasticsearch already defaults to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs`, I can mount an emptyDir there and have Filebeat read from it. I need to override the log4j2 configuration to write application logs to files instead of just stdout, since the default ES 8.x Docker image only logs to stdout.\n\nFor Filebeat to collect logs, I could use the container input type with a hostPath mount to `/var/log/pods`, but that's getting complex. Let me refocus on what's actually required: Metricbeat and Filebeat sidecars that both ship to the monitoring cluster, with the logs path being the key constraint I need to solve.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to configure Elasticsearch to write JSON logs to a file by overriding the log4j2.properties through a ConfigMap, then mount that file in both the ES container and the Filebeat sidecar via an emptyDir volume. I need to check what the default log4j2.properties looks like in ES 8.11.1 to understand how to properly configure it.\n\nAdding file-based JSON logging... I could mount the emptyDir in both containers so ES writes logs to it and Filebeat reads from it, which avoids needing host-level access. I'll create a custom log4j2.properties ConfigMap with a JSON file appender, mount it in the ES container, and set up the shared volume for logs between ES and Filebeat.\n\nWriting log4j2 config... Configuring the rolling file appender with time-based and size-based rotation policies, setting it to roll daily and when files exceed 128MB, then defining a cleanup strategy that deletes old log files matching the cluster name pattern. I'm reconsidering whether to use EcsLayout or a simpler PatternLayout for the log output, but I'm realizing this approach might be overcomplicating things. Maybe instead of trying to capture ES application logs to files, I should leverage Filebeat to read the GC logs that are already being written.\n\nActually, the most straightforward solution is to set up a shared emptyDir volume for logs between the ES container and Filebeat, configure log4j2 to write JSON-formatted logs to that directory, and have Filebeat ingest those files to send to the monitoring cluster. Let me verify the default log paths and system properties that Elasticsearch uses, then I'll create a custom log4j2.properties file that enables file logging for JSON server logs alongside the GC logs that are already being written to the shared volume. at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs`, then mount that same volume in Filebeat as read-only so it can ingest the JSON logs. Before finalizing the log4j2 configuration, I should check what the current setup looks like in the ES container to make sure I'm building on the right foundation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":406,"cache_read_input_tokens":46109,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":406},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34b30af3-95da-40fc-b631-05bf5531cd48","uuid":"73c60405-1cb9-480c-a73b-89b96824bf51","request_id":"req_011CcMbDNxRmzN3UkB1sXoRV"}
