{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PaD981rZTuwVytN4Bd1tex","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see two issues:\n\n1. **Metricbeat** is getting \"connection refused\" on `https://localhost:9200`. This means ES isn't yet ready (the pod just restarted) OR there's a networking issue. Actually, looking at the pod status - es-0 was just restarted 87s ago. The ES container might still be starting up. The readinessProbe for ES has `initialDelaySeconds: 45`, so it might not be fully ready yet. Let me check.\n\nWait, the pod is 3/3 Running, which means all containers passed their readiness checks. But metricbeat is getting \"connection refused\"... \n \nHmm, the ES readinessProbe checks if the HTTPS endpoint returns a 200 or 401 status code, and since the pod shows 3/3 READY, all containers including ES passed their checks. Yet metricbeat is still hitting connection refused. That's odd—maybe metricbeat's readiness probe is different or it doesn't have one, so it could be marked ready even though it can't actually reach ES yet.\n\nLooking at the error timestamps around 06:20:03 to 06:20:23, the pods became fully ready about 27 minutes after startup, but metricbeat might be trying to connect before ES is actually stable enough to accept connections.\n\nThe Filebeat mapper error is clearer though — I set `fields_under_root: true` with a `service: elasticsearch` field, but the monitoring index already has `service` as an object field from the ECS JSON data that Elasticsearch logs. When Filebeat tries to write a string value for `service` to an index expecting an object, it fails. I need to either remove `fields_under_root` or rename the conflicting field. The real issue is that `fields_under_root: true` combined with my custom `service` field creates a conflict—`service` can't be both a string and a nested object. I should remove the `service` field from the Filebeat config to resolve this. Actually, 