{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PMt5h9f6A3Tk1fWBuTQRQG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The last log entry is 06:27:25. These are connection refused errors. But the pod was in 3/3 Ready at 06:28:something. Let me check the current time and see if the errors have stopped.\n\nWait, but the container is Ready and `curl https://localhost:9200` works! So why is metricbeat still getting connection refused?\n\nOH WAIT. I just realized something. The metricbeat container is using `runAsUser: 0` (root). Let me check if there might be an IPv6 vs IPv4 issue. \n\nI'm noticing the errors reference both IPv6 loopback addresses and IPv4 loopback addresses—maybe Elasticsearch is only listening on IPv4 but metricbeat is attempting IPv6 first? The readiness probe works fine with `curl -sk https://localhost:9200`, yet metricbeat keeps hitting connection refused. Let me check what network ports are actually open in the pod to understand what's happening.\n\nThe startup timing might be the culprit here. Elasticsearch takes time to fully listen on port 9200 during initialization, even though the readiness probe eventually passes. Metricbeat starts simultaneously and tries connecting right away, retrying every 10 seconds. The errors stopped appearing around 06:27:25, which suggests metricbeat likely succeeded once Elasticsearch finished its startup sequence and the pod became ready. The real question is whether metricbeat is currently connecting successfully or still failing.\n\nLooking at the monitoring index, it still shows 11 documents unchanged since before the restart, which is concerning. If metricbeat had successfully reconnected and started writing metrics again, I'd expect to see new documents by now. This suggests the connection might still not be working despite the pod showing as Ready. So the restart order was es-2, then es-1, then es-0 (standard StatefulSet rolling update from highest to low